    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i have a physics exam coming up and i'm struggling a bit with the concept of quantum entanglement. can you give me a concise, non-mathematical summary of what it actually is and how it's different from just regular classical correlation? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two or more particles become linked in such a way that the state of one particle instantly influences the state of the other, no matter how far apart they are. This is different from classical correlation, where objects can be correlated but do not have this instant, instantaneous connection. In classical correlation, information about one object doesn't affect the other, while in quantum entanglement, the state of one particle is dependent on the state of the other, even if separated by vast distances. It's like having two magical coins that always land on the same side whenever you flip them, even if they're on opposite sides of the galaxy.",
      "source": "target",
