    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "the coin thing makes sense but it still feels a bit weird. i've heard people call it \"spooky action at a distance\" - what did einstein mean by that exactly? why was he so uncomfortable with it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Albert Einstein referred to quantum entanglement as \"spooky action at a distance\" because it seemed to defy the classical understanding of the universe where objects are only influenced by their immediate surroundings. He believed that entanglement suggested that information could somehow travel faster than the speed of light, which contradicted the theory of relativity that says nothing can go faster than light. Einstein, along with others like Niels Bohr, found this aspect of quantum mechanics quite unsettling because it challenged the idea of local realism, the belief that objects have definite properties whether or not we observe them, and that these properties are not influenced by events happening far away. Einstein even proposed a thought experiment called \"EPR paradox\" to argue against the completeness of quantum mechanics.\n\nDespite his initial discomfort, Einstein eventually acknowledged that quantum entanglement is a real phenomenon and agreed that it could not be explained by local hidden variables, as quantum mechanics suggests. Nevertheless, he remained puzzled by its implications, famously saying, \"God does not play dice with the universe,\" highlighting his unease with the probabilistic nature of quantum mechanics. Over time, however, the strange and counterintuitive nature of entanglement has become an accepted cornerstone of quantum physics.",
      "source": "target",
