    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "so if it's not about information traveling faster than light, how does the connection actually work? like, if a particle is measured here, how does the other one 'know' to change its state instantly? it still sounds a bit like some kind of hidden trick or something.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The connection in quantum entanglement doesn't involve any actual signal traveling between the entangled particles, so it doesn't violate the speed of light limit. When two particles are entangled, they share a joint quantum state; this means their properties are correlated in a way that can't be described separately. When you measure one particle, its state becomes determined, and because of the entanglement, the state of the other particle is instantly correlated to match this new state. This \"instant knowing\" isn't due to any hidden signaling but rather an intrinsic property of the entangled system, which is a result of the principles of quantum mechanics.\n\n\nTo use your coin analogy, imagine you have two coins that always land on the same side when you flip them, even if they're on opposite sides of the universe. The coins don't send a signal to each other; they simply always land on the same side because they're entangled. This is fundamentally different from classical objects that can be correlated through hidden variables or signals. The entanglement is an inherent property of the quantum state of the system, not something that happens after the fact or due to some external influence. It's a bit like magic, but not trickery; it's just a different kind of reality that quantum mechanics describes",
      "source": "target",
      "gen_token_ids": [
        976,
        6703,
        306,
        48889,
        1121,
        516,
        1254,
        8740,
        28726,
